Unlike the approach typical of architectural survey,Nair chooses analytic depth to exposit the details of asingle architectural complex. Each chapter articulatesthe versatile ways in which the Inca gave weight andmeaning to space and to how royal authority was constructed.Ultimately,NairsworkidentifiesthearchitecturalsignatureofTopaIncaanddemonstrateshisagencyin design and building. Social history is carefully interwovenwithdiscussionofmaterialityandwaysofexperiencing architecture. The narrative is unified by thevocabularyofarchitectureanditsQuechualanguagereferents.Basedonoveradecadeofresearch,onethatprioritizes field study and a deep reading of colonialdictionaries, At Home with the Sapa Inca promises acomprehensiveperspectiveonthetopic.Anditdelivers.
Thebookisorganizedbychaptersreferringtobuilding features or places. A preface in which Quechuaorthographyisexplainedwillbeparticularlywelcomedby readers unaccustomed to the regional language.Completingthebookareextensivenotes,abibliography,andindex.Archaeologistswillnotfindexcavationplansorstratigraphicdrawingswithinthebookspages,butthesearedutifullyreferencedinthetext,notes,andbibliography.
Inahighlyinformativeintroductorychapter,therulerand his family history provide a starting point forChincheros history. Spanning several centuries to thepresent day, the sites history is critical to interpretingwhatremainsoftheIncaimprint.Acleartheoreticalperspective is also delineated, as are Nairs objectives.Anideographic approach to architecture grounded in phenomenological theory serves as the framework for thestudy. Architecture is acknowledged as a threedimensional entity in which space is created and in whichmovement is carefully articulated to construct distinctexperiences.Thisapproachdepartsfrommapbased,andtoacertainextent,GISbasedsurvey,inwhichlandscapevistasareunseen,asarethevisualrelationshipsbetweenbuildings that architecture affords from an experientiallevel. 
Chapter 1, Pirca/Wall, establishes the fundamentalsforarchitecturalanalysis.Attentionisdevotedtoanalyticalcategoriesthatwillbefamiliartomostinvestigators:building type, form, facture, materials, and patronage.Thechapterofferstwomajorcontributions:thattheIncabuilding type was not based on form, and that facture,materiality,andpatronagewereoffargreaterconcerntotheInca.Thekallankaisthecenterpiece,here.Originallyan Inca construction term, the word is used in contemporary literature to describe a building according to its sizeandshape.Nairarguesthattherectangleisthebasicconstruction unit and that its scale does not necessarilymake it a building type. Building materials and factureare stronger indicators of a buildings identity.
AwiderspatialandtemporalperspectiveisemployedinChapter2,Pacha/PlaceandTime.Aconvincinganalysis of how Chinchero became place is articulatedthrough concrete examples of roads and monuments.Nairshowshowtherulersdesignallowedhimtomanipulate movement to and from the site and to capture theterritoriesofhisrivalsbyestablishingsubtlearchitecturalgestures along roads.Also critical is her analysis of theterraces and stone places in the wider landscape: Chincana, Condorcaca, Titicaca. These monuments may befamiliar to students of Inca architecture, but here, Nairencourages us to experience Topa Incas heavyhandedpresencefromtheinsideandpersuadesusthatthepathsand routes by which we are directed are highly choreographed.
The great stage on which the Inca established communication betweenthe stateanditslocalinhabitantsis discussed in Chapter 3, Pampa/Plaza. Nair underscoresthe importance of these enormous open spaces as morethan meeting places for pageants and large crowds.Instead, her detailed analysis addresses how the plazaswere used and by whom, the entrances and exits thatdirected the royals and their crowds, and the sacredandquotidian spaces often overlooked in their analysis.
Royal building types are analyzed in Chapter 4,Puncu/Doorway.Thechapterbeginswithanexplanationof the puncu, or opening, that defines building types onroyalestates.Nair shows how puncusframedandmonitoredvisualorientationsbetweenbuildingsandspaces.A major finding here is a building type introduced byTopaInca,knownasthecuyusmanco.Equallyimportant isthe carpauasi,notfoundatChinchero,butcharacteristic of the poorly studied Huaytar. Throughout thechapter, Nair demonstrates that structures evolved overtime, and that individual rulers possessed the agency to create new ones. 
AnumberofdistinctstructuresarediscussedinChapter 5, Uasi/House, in which the focus on interior spacesiskey.Notableisthevestibule, or camachiconauasi,inwhich a buried offering is strategically placed at theentrance.SpecialmentionisdeservingofNairsanalysisofthegalpn,atermfrequentlycitedincolonialsourcesas a shed, and later, a prison. Nair traces the term tosixteenthcentury Nicaragua and links it to the PipilNawattermkalpoloroldlargehouse.Nairslinguistichousekeepingreclarifiesthisandothertermsrelativetoarchitectural forms. 
